After several weeks of research, programming, tinkering and a little frustration, I was finally able to download a picture of a specific region from Geomapapp, convert it to an stl file, and print it on the 3-D printer.  I am pretty sure it is Mt Rainier.

As I said in the comments section, I am working on a user friendly version for my friend's middle school geology class by March. For now, if you want to make one here is what I did.
1) Download and run GeoMapApp.
2) Get the thing you want to print in your viewing window.
3) Turn off the sun, switch palette to black to white.
4) Select "Save map file as image/grid file" and save as a .png
5) Open .png file in paint and crop the Lat and Long border.
6) Install stl_tools (github) library for python.
7) Use stl_tools to convert the .png to an .stl
8) Print and enjoy.

description.text:
This is a spinner made from the Fablab logo. It uses a 608 bearing and 3 or 6 (better) coins of 0.1 € (not 0.2€ as previously stated). It can be customized by downloading the scad file and the DXF file.

Will be better with a R188 bearing ...

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

No

Infill:

15% at least

Notes:

You need to print this thing with thicker than usual walls. To keep this spinner to a usable size for every hands I had to reduce it to a size where the walls are very thin near the bearing. Because of that you must configure you're slicer in order to have a 100% infill in this area. The best way I found is to increase the wall thickness.
Can be quite fragile under 15% of infill.

Depending on your printer accuracy you will be able or not to insert the coins and the bearing by pressing firmly on it by hand or with a vice. If it doesn't work do not try too hard or you might break the spinner. Use a heat source to soften the PLA before to insert the bearing and the coins.

The Fablag logo was cut to keep only one branch. Using Openscad I imported the branch, extruded it, and copy/rotate it three times. It will not work in customizer as it is not possible to import a DXF. But you can download the files and customize it at will.

title: Mavic Pro Spring Loaded Adjustable Tablet / Phone Holder

description.text:
Large and Small size spring loaded adjustable tablet or phone holders for use with the DJI Mavic Pro RC controller.

Two bases with or without a notch if you keep the phone connector installed on the controller.

All you need to complete would be a properly sized 1/4" diameter extension type spring, I bought about a 6" spring and just clipped it to get the amount of tension I wanted.

You'll also need one 1/4 x 20 x 1 1/2 socket head bolt and nut and washer, if you use the knob with the bolt, then insert the bolt into the knob with some medium CA to hold it snug inside the knob.

A couple of small nails will be needed, or in my case I had a couple of small rivets to hold the spring in place, I then trimmed off the ends flush, you can apply a small dab of medium CA on the ends of the pins holding the spring so they don't come out.

The print orientation is the same as the pictures.

I just used .35mm layer and 100% infill for strength, no supports anywhere.

description.text:
The Airy Arm is an exoskeletal device that was designed to assist individuals with an intact but non-functioning hand. When wearing the device, the user would extend his or her elbow, and the device would in turn extend their fingers via cables. No electronic components are used. For more information, please see the Guide.

This is still the most recent version of the Airy Arm. This device has not been successfully tested for safety or efficacy!! Please use with caution! It is an experimental prototype, which I am sharing so that others may continue developing it.

All files have been uploaded here in STL for direct printing, STEP for imported editing, and SLDPRT for native SolidWorks users. Also included is a Guide that walks through assembly, and a document which outlines my design explorations, such that any individual or group who wishes to further this project might learn from my experiences. If anyone does wish to do so, please share your device under a different name, to avoid confusion in the future.

Thank you for helping to further this project.

-Added letters (L&R) to the parts to indicate left and right. Updated the left and right carriages to use M5 nuts instead of using the carriage itself as a nut for the idlers screws (easier to work with) and slightly adjusted their design. check the last rendering picture. Changed all the idlers to F695zz Flanged Bearing 5x13x4mm and updated almost all the parts to fit the new idlers. 26/01.2018

Now you can 3D view or download the raw design in multiple formats to edit it easily (if you want to).
http://a360.co/2Bv5o4T

Video about all the changes I made to my FT-5:
https://youtu.be/JWi-ZnHx8co

FT5 Accurate Adjustable Z Endstop:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tF2z4EKhI4I

  • 13X M5*10mm screws and T-nuts (to hold mounts on 2020 profiles).
  • 1X M3*8mm screw (for X Endstop).
  • X16 Idlers F695zz Flanged Bearing 5x13x4mm.
  • Steel-core belt is a plus.
  • Carriages screws: 8X M310mm for Y and 4X M38mm for X. 2X M3*20mm screws and nylon lock nuts (to hold the X rail).
  • 4X M3*30mm screws and nuts (for belts tensioners).
  • 6X M5*45mm and 8X M5 nuts (for idlers).
  • For the back M5 idler screw holes, I drilled them with 4.5mm drilling bit, so I can use the screws without nuts (so the plastic will be the nut) but you can drill them with 5mm bit and use M5 nuts.
  • The extruder mount got 4 holes in case you want to make adapters for something like BLtouch or cables box etc..

The motors side is the front side!
 Use support for the part "belt tensioner/mount" but don't use support for its belt teeth. When inserting the belts into the tensioners, be gentle with the little lever, open it very slightly to insert the belt or you might break it.
This design requires a long nozzle or Volcano setup.
 Use high quality idlers!! I used the cheap ones, and they are not spinning 100% in center, and that leads to print quality issues!
No need to extend any wires for the motors or X endstop, the stock wires are long enough.
 I used 3X M360mm screws with nuts to hold the extruder assembly all the way from the back of the short stepper to the Aero heatsink (I removed 3 screws from the stepper).
Make sure to orient the parts to the proper orientation before printing (depends on how the part is stressed). I'll change the orientations later for you. I used 4 walls, 4 top, 4 bottom, 50% infill.
 Don't forget to remove the "//" before "#define COREXY" to enable CoreXY kinematics.
Make sure all idlers/belts are in their correct height, the belts should always be horizontal at any point!
 If you are going to use high bed temps, don't use PLA for the part "bed spacer", you can also ignore this part and use m360mm screw as a bed spacer as shown in the picture (I used 80mm screws temporarily).
** Use a stiff material, preferably heat resistance like CF-PETG, CF-nylon CF-ABS. Anything could work tho even PLA.

Idlers F695zz Flanged Bearing 5x13x4mm X16 :https://goo.gl/Wfv45t

User of AM8 (Anet Metal A8) and Anet A8, must print a mirror of the base. Pointer is the same for both machines.
To mount the pointer, use a M4 x 16 flat head screw and a M4 nylon lock nut.
User of AM8 use 2 M5 x 10 button head socket head screw and two hammer nuts.
User of Anet A8, must drill two 3mm holes on each side about 3/8" apart. and at the same height on both sides to allow for adjustment and make sure that the pointer reach over the smooth rod.
To install:
AM8 user, measure from top of bottom 2040 to indicating line of the base making sure is the exact same on both sides.
Anet A8 users, do the same but use the top of the motor mounts as reference.
To set up the height, rotate the indicator pointer counter clockwise on the right side, clockwise on the left side and have them rest on the screws. Bring the carriage close to the device, until you are able to rest both pointer on the smooth rods, bring both sides up until the pointer tip marked as shown in the photo aligns with the tip on the base on both sides. do not forget to bring the pointers back to resting on the screws before homing.
Hopefully will help a little bit.

This is my entry for the Makerbot giveaway. It is a first draft of a 1/3 scale model/design inspired by a Zenith K-518 clock radio from 1953 (see included image) that I am currently restoring. The original pictured is about 12-in x 4.5-in x 6-in in size. It was one of the last years Zenith used Bakelite in its radios. The design presented would be used in the construction a working model AM radio (like the original), which would feature a clock on the left side, a ~1-inch speaker mounted behind the grill in the center, and the tuning panel on the right. The lower left nob would be volume control (and possibly a click-on-off switch...although those are a bit tougher to get at this size), and the right nob would be the tuning control. As far as size of the cabinet goes (about 4-in x 1.4-in x 2-in), the design presented could be shifted up or down in order to accommodate the restrictions of the printer. I have a feeling the speaker grill may be too fine as it is to be printed reliably, although I would need the expertise of someone to confirm that. makezine.com/go/makerbot http://blog.makezine.com/archive/2010/04/makerbot_giveaway.html When I converted it over to STL, it does seem to have messed up the scale in the file, so I'll have to look into that.

The stl file attached contains everything for the design.  I am sure one would need to split this up for actual fab.  
The actual circuit would be pretty run-of-the-mill and probably based around one of the single-chip AM radios which are manufactured such as a TEA555IT by Philips.  The tuning cap would probably need to be connected to the tuning nob through a tensioned-string of some sort...just like in the original.  I would love to use subminiature tubes in order to keep with the miniature glass tube technology of the original but even those are too big for the case presented.

description.text:
This is a remix of two popular power supply covers for reprap printers (Anet A8 and a Sells Mendal).

UPDATE: I added a version without my name recess on the right side of the print.

I have modified the two of these covers to work with the Anet A8 vertical mounting position allowing for an upgrade to the eTopxizu 30amp power supply. I have moved the rear most hole forward a few mm to align the screws slightly better. I have also increased the width of the front plate compared to what is pictured, the front plate area now extends beneath the right most part of the socket.

The hole for the socket should fit the IEC320 C14 or a socket of similar design, there are many of them out on the inter-webs. The power supply will need a conversion bracket to be secured to the Anet A8 frame, this bracket was designed by Wotever and can be found here:
www.thingiverse.com/thing:1641334

The bracket will move the power supply away from the frame and allow the cover to wrap around the back side of the case.

I would like to thank thingiverse users rullmann and Puddlefist for their original designs. Without their original hard work I would have had a much harder time designing this. If they see this and would like their logos included with mine, please send me a message.

Please let me know if you have any questions, comments or concerns! Go lay down some layers!

I use rafts because I have a hard time getting first layer adhesion on my BuildTak but if you get first layer I doubt you need rafts. I think I printed at 38 mm/s, 1.2 walls at 0.9 mm first layer. Turned out better than I expected, fit first try no finishing required.

description.text:
This is a low profile direct drive TItan carriage design that works on all 8mm rod style Prusa Printers.

Here are the main features of the carriage design;

*Low profile design and light weight; The Carriage design was an idea which the main goal was to create a low profile carriage that would only need 2 bearings/bushings to work and still be strong and accurate enough to put out good quality prints. To make this happen all the weight and forces would have to be as near center on the rods as possible to eliminate any binding or any amplification in free play. The total weight of all 3 printed pieces at 45% Infill is 59.6g

*Bearing holders are designed to be used with typical SK8U Bearing or an Igus bushing. A small lip is at each end of the bearing holder to help retain an Igus bushing without needing to put unnecessary amount clamping force to hold bushing in carriage, which would cause binding.

*No ziptie belt system which is easy to install and extremely secure.
